<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n11143c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n11" href="#n11143c">N11 (VI.B.5)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n11all.htm#n11143c"> 143(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> night dances of druidesses / scare Romans</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">C&eacute;sar vint battre ici avec sa flotte. La dune m&ecirc;me qui porte le village de Bourg-de-Batz aurait &eacute;t&eacute; alors, selon la tradition, cette &icirc;le o&ugrave; les pr&ecirc;tresses namn&egrave;tes se livraient &agrave; <mark>des danses nocturnes qui &eacute;pouvantaient les navigateurs</mark>, et d&apos;o&ugrave; elles partaient myst&eacute;rieusement dans leurs barques pour rejoindre leurs &eacute;poux par les nuits de pleine lune. Le castrum romain a chass&eacute; les sorci&egrave;res gauloises de leur retraite. <br><font color="green">[Caesar came here to fight with his fleet. The same dune which carries the village of Bourg-de-Batz would then have been, according to tradition, this island where the nametian priestesses indulged in nocturnal dances which terrified the navigators, and from which they left mysteriously in their boats to join their husbands on the nights of full moon. The Roman castrum chased the Gallic witches from their retreat.]</font> <small> &Eacute;douard Schur&eacute;, <a name="ESLG" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ESLG"><cite title="source">Les Grandes L&eacute;gendes de France</cite></a> (1921, 1892) 200</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
